question_title: How many dissenting votes will there be at the January 28, 2026 Federal Open Market Committee meeting?
summary: The January 2026 FOMC meeting will have different voting dynamics than December 2025 due to the rotation of regional Fed presidents. Two key December dissenters (Schmid and Goolsbee) are rotating off, replaced by Logan (very hawkish), Hammack (neutral), Kashkari (neutral/hawkish), and Paulson (dovish). However, Stephen Miran remains as a permanent voter and has dissented at every meeting since his appointment (September, October, December 2025), consistently wanting faster rate cuts. With the Fed expected to hold rates in January, Miran is highly likely to dissent again. The most probable outcome is 1 dissent (Miran alone), with moderate probability of 2 dissents if the dovish Paulson joins him. The probability of 0 dissents is low given Miran's consistent pattern, while 3+ is less likely since the most frequent dissenters have rotated off.

factors.description: Stephen Miran has dissented at every FOMC meeting since joining (3 consecutive: Sept, Oct, Dec 2025), consistently advocating for faster rate cuts. This near-perfect record strongly suggests he will dissent again.
Two of the three December dissenters (Schmid and Goolsbee) are rotating off the committee, reducing the base of likely dissenters.
The Fed is expected to hold rates in January 2026 rather than cut, which would trigger Miran's dissent pattern (he wants cuts) but satisfy the hawkish new members.
New rotating member Anna Paulson (Philadelphia) is described as dovish, making her a potential second dissenter if Fed holds rates.
New rotating member Lorie Logan (Dallas) is described as 'very hawkish' - unlikely to dissent if Fed holds, but could dissent if Fed cuts.
The 2025 pattern shows increasing willingness to dissent (0→2→1→2→3), suggesting a cultural shift away from unanimity, though the specific dissenters matter.
